summary: 14 years experience in the Intelligence community conducting signals analysis and reporting. SUMMARY OF QUALIFICATIONS •Top Secret/SCI Clearance, exp. 2017. CI Polygraph conducted June 2009. •14 years analytical experience as a Signal/Intelligence Analyst with the United States Army, Lockheed Martin Corporation, L3 STRATIS, and Northrop Grumman. EXPERIENCE Analysis •Certified on 5 real time systems conducting analog and digital signal processing. •Provided over 300 time sensitive reports for national level consumers. •Proficient in use of computer applications, intelligence software, and hardware tools: Microsoft Office, LINUX, UNIX, XBIT, MARTES, BLACKMAGIC, Wave and Data Viewer Tools, ORQAM, User Interface System, OILSTOCK, Spectrum Analyzers, Oscilloscopes, Receivers, Frequency Counters, and Demodulators. Leadership and Interpersonal Skills •Experienced and skilled in providing briefings to superiors and effective instruction, training, and directions to subordinates in support of Intelligence Collection. •Supervised in 3 signal development centers supporting a 24/7 watch. •Served as Army Liaison and Mentoring officer at Communications and Signals course; writing student reports, handling issues, and providing academic assistance. Training •Certified Senior Joint Service School Instructor for Basic Communication Signals course. •Trained over 300 students and 4 classes with a GPA 3% above course average. •Certified 11 analysts on real time analog and digital signal collection positions. EDUCATION •B.A. Intelligence Studies GPA 3.77, American Military University August 2012 •A.A.S. Intelligence Operations GPA 4.0, Cochise College, AZ May 2009 •U.S. Army: Intermediate Communication Signals Analysis Course, Journeyman Instructor Training, Primary leadership Course, Advanced Communication Intelligence (COMINT) Mapping, Basic COMINT Mapping, Basic Communication Signals Course.

EXPERIENCE Analysis •Certified on 5 real time systems conducting analog and digital signal processing. •Provided over 300 time sensitive reports for national level consumers. •Proficient in use of computer applications, intelligence software, and hardware tools: Microsoft Office, LINUX, UNIX, XBIT, MARTES, BLACKMAGIC, Wave and Data Viewer Tools, ORQAM, User Interface System, OILSTOCK, Spectrum Analyzers, Oscilloscopes, Receivers, Frequency Counters, and Demodulators. Leadership and Interpersonal Skills •Experienced and skilled in providing briefings to superiors and effective instruction, training, and directions to subordinates in support of Intelligence Collection. •Supervised in 3 signal development centers supporting a 24/7 watch. •Served as Army Liaison and Mentoring officer at Communications and Signals course; writing student reports, handling issues, and providing academic assistance. Training •Certified Senior Joint Service School Instructor for Basic Communication Signals course. •Trained over 300 students and 4 classes with a GPA 3% above course average. •Certified 11 analysts on real time analog and digital signal collection positions. EDUCATION •B.A. Intelligence Studies GPA 3.77, American Military University August 2012 •A.A.S. Intelligence Operations GPA 4.0, Cochise College, AZ May 2009 •U.S. Army: Intermediate Communication Signals Analysis Course, Journeyman Instructor Training, Primary leadership Course, Advanced Communication Intelligence (COMINT) Mapping, Basic COMINT Mapping, Basic Communication Signals Course.

description: Program Manager for two telecommunications analysis projects, supervising 40 analysts and support personnel charged with all-source and imagery analysis of a variety of telecommunications networks and systems, worldwide. Responsibilities: * Daily operation of projects & assignment of analytical tasking. * Technical supervision. * Telecommunications analysis & review of analytical products and deliverables. * Reporting status of projects to General Dynamics and client management teams. These reports included extensive information and analyses on specific telecommunications systems with maps, photographs and technical data.

description: Senior Intelligence/Imagery Analyst and deputy program manager for a project producing in-depth analysis of telecommunications networks on a worldwide basis. * Provided technical leadership and network analysis skills required to produce products supporting customer operations. * Prepared and delivered time-sensitive reports and studies supporting customer requirements. * Implemented the purchase and employment of ArcView GIS software and an Electronic Light Table software package allowing for the production of digital products. * Instrumental in the purchase of a digital imagery scanner. * Managed the collection of historical telecommunications data from various corporate sites, which could be used in the analysis of worldwide telecommunications systems and included as a part of customer directed studies. * Briefed both General Dynamics and customer management on the status of technical projects and data collection.

summary: HR professional with 8 years of experience specializing in talent acquisition. Full life cycle recruitment experience in both the commercial and federal space to include Department of Defense (DoD) and the Intelligence Community (IC). Actively recruit skill sets to include a full spectrum of IT, Engineering and Intelligence Services both CONUS and OCONUS. Proven ability to maintain relationships and ensure customer satisfaction. Active Top Secret security clearance. Connection requests are welcome!

description: • Lead recruiting efforts for industry and federal customer base to include: Electrical/Mechanical Engineers, Critical Facility Technicians, Project Managers, Directors, Data Center Facility Techs and Managers with a TS/SCI • Participate in special assignments related to developing new or revised recruitment programs and practices. • Develop relationships with Senior Management and assist to identify recruitment needs. • Conduct full cycle recruitment and on-boarding procedures for local and remote site locations • Perform a variety of HR areas including benefits, employee relations, training, recruitment, salary/wage administration, and (ADP) payroll • Maintain company ATS database and collect data/prepared related statistical reports • Provide guidance to all levels of employees regarding personnel policies, benefits and procedures • Implement 401k plan for remote site in Puerto Rico • Facilitate weekly new hire orientations • COBRA administration and exit interviews • Maintain Affirmative Action plan and respond to OFCCP (desk) audit request(s) • Experience with Unions and CBA’s

summary: Lindsey is a three year member of the Talent Acquisition group at Battelle Memorial Institute in Columbus, Ohio. Battelle is the world’s largest nonprofit research and development organization, generating over $4B in revenue annually in global R&D. In her role at Battelle, Lindsey is responsible for defining new recruiting processes and initiatives while supporting National Security, Energy, Health & Environment, Lab Operations as well as exclusively staffing Chemical Demilitarization sites in Pueblo, CO and Richmond, KY. Lindsey is also responsible for our Military Recruiting Strategy and Military Community Outreach Program. Prior to joining Battelle, Lindsey worked for Mission Essential; a government contractor headquartered in Columbus, Ohio. For over a decade Mission Essential has served customers at the strategic and tactical levels, providing operational solutions to the U.S. Department of Defense, State, and Homeland Security; the Intelligence Community; friendly foreign government; and multinational corporations. Lindsey specialized in performing all complex elements of a variety of professional and administrative recruiting functions in support of identifying, interviewing, evaluating, and selecting qualified, government cleared professionals (ranging from Interim Secret to TS/SCI full scope poly) to effectively meet multiple requirements in support of military rotation exercises and Department of Defense government contracts CONUS and OCONUS. Lindsey is currently working with the U.S. Special Operations Command to develop a Fellowship Program for wounded Special Forces Veterans and is also engaged in planning and operating a quarterly Jobs for Veterans Workshop. Lindsey has over 6 years of diverse HR experience as well as government contracting/ recruiting experience and has a Bachelor’s degree in Sociology from The Ohio State University.

summary: Lindsey is a three year member of the Talent Acquisition group at Battelle Memorial Institute in Columbus, Ohio. Battelle is the world’s largest nonprofit research and development organization, generating over $4B in revenue annually in global R&D. In her role at Battelle, Lindsey is responsible for defining new recruiting processes and initiatives while supporting National Security, Energy, Health & Environment, Lab Operations as well as exclusively staffing Chemical Demilitarization sites in Pueblo, CO and Richmond, KY. Lindsey is also responsible for our Military Recruiting Strategy and Military Community Outreach Program. Prior to joining Battelle, Lindsey worked for Mission Essential; a government contractor headquartered in Columbus, Ohio. For over a decade Mission Essential has served customers at the strategic and tactical levels, providing operational solutions to the U.S. Department of Defense, State, and Homeland Security; the Intelligence Community; friendly foreign government; and multinational corporations. Lindsey specialized in performing all complex elements of a variety of professional and administrative recruiting functions in support of identifying, interviewing, evaluating, and selecting qualified, government cleared professionals (ranging from Interim Secret to TS/SCI full scope poly) to effectively meet multiple requirements in support of military rotation exercises and Department of Defense government contracts CONUS and OCONUS. Lindsey is currently working with the U.S. Special Operations Command to develop a Fellowship Program for wounded Special Forces Veterans and is also engaged in planning and operating a quarterly Jobs for Veterans Workshop. Lindsey has over 6 years of diverse HR experience as well as government contracting/ recruiting experience and has a Bachelor’s degree in Sociology from The Ohio State University.

description: Battelle is the world’s largest nonprofit independent research and development organization, providing innovative solutions to the world’s most pressing needs through its four global businesses: Laboratory Management, National Security, Energy Technology, and Health and Life Sciences. It advances scientific discovery and application by conducting $5.2 billion in global R&D annually through contract research, laboratory management and technology commercialization. Headquartered in Columbus, Ohio, Battelle oversees 20,400 employees in more than 130 cities worldwide, including seven national laboratories that Battelle manages or co-manages for the U.S. Department of Energy and the U.S. Department of Homeland Security and two international laboratories—a nuclear energy lab in the United Kingdom and a renewable energy lab in Malaysia.

summary: Lindsey is a three year member of the Talent Acquisition group at Battelle Memorial Institute in Columbus, Ohio. Battelle is the world’s largest nonprofit research and development organization, generating over $4B in revenue annually in global R&D. In her role at Battelle, Lindsey is responsible for defining new recruiting processes and initiatives while supporting National Security, Energy, Health & Environment, Lab Operations as well as exclusively staffing Chemical Demilitarization sites in Pueblo, CO and Richmond, KY. Lindsey is also responsible for our Military Recruiting Strategy and Military Community Outreach Program. Prior to joining Battelle, Lindsey worked for Mission Essential; a government contractor headquartered in Columbus, Ohio. For over a decade Mission Essential has served customers at the strategic and tactical levels, providing operational solutions to the U.S. Department of Defense, State, and Homeland Security; the Intelligence Community; friendly foreign government; and multinational corporations. Lindsey specialized in performing all complex elements of a variety of professional and administrative recruiting functions in support of identifying, interviewing, evaluating, and selecting qualified, government cleared professionals (ranging from Interim Secret to TS/SCI full scope poly) to effectively meet multiple requirements in support of military rotation exercises and Department of Defense government contracts CONUS and OCONUS. Lindsey is currently working with the U.S. Special Operations Command to develop a Fellowship Program for wounded Special Forces Veterans and is also engaged in planning and operating a quarterly Jobs for Veterans Workshop. Lindsey has over 6 years of diverse HR experience as well as government contracting/ recruiting experience and has a Bachelor’s degree in Sociology from The Ohio State University.

description: Intelligence and Imagery Analyst. Duties include monitoring, assessing, and presenting strategic and tactical intelligence to senior leadership and inquiring customers. Experienced live imagery analyst providing ground forces with accurate and timely information through secure satellite and tactical military communications. Daily analysis of live and forensic data associated with threat assessment and security functions regarding military, political, and social issues influencing relations in the Middle East. Responsible for training and supervising new team members and insuring operational security measures are maintained. Tracking and Imagery Intelligence Analyst. Live review of GMTI movement around various parts of Iraq. Cooperative Intelligence analysis with HUMINT, SIGINT, MASINT and All Source personnel to give chain of command overall picture of mission progression. Provided training to new personnel on mission requirements, mock deployed missions and RFI’s. Conducted post mission analysis of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan. Assisted SSO in securing all classified documentation and systems in the Intelligence Cell. Monitored all personnel as a security supervisor for the Intelligence Training Center of Operations (ITCO) and G2 sections. Responsible for daily status reports for all III Corps and in/out processing personnel. •Trained new personnel on the G2 Intelligence Cell requirements for both CONUS and OCNUS mission standards. •Conducted regular security threat checks, insuring all sections maintained individual OPSEC, and maintained all Corps personnel records, unit files, and DISTRO lists. •Examination of pre and post mission data from deployed environments to aid in USF-I operations as well as training purposes.

description: Multi-source and Full Motion Video Analyst (MSA/FMV) – Processing, Exploitation and Dissemination Crew • Certified in three Processing, Exploitation, and Dissemination crew positions • 2500+ hours of processing and exploiting intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance full-motion video in support of special operations forces • Created and disseminated over 250 FMV and all source intelligence products used by special operations forces and decision makers servicing in OIF and OEF • Responsible for conducting target research and pattern of life analysis per customer request and real-time data basing of new target data in support of the special operations mission using programs such as MAAS, Falconview, mIRC, ArcGis, Microsoft Powerpoint, Excel, Videobank and GoogleEarth MSA Subject Matter Expert (SME) / Instructor Rated Operator (IRO) – Department of Training • Tracked and maintained the training statuses and qualifications of 250+ employees using Microsoft Excel and Access databases, handling over 60 requests for upgrade training, evaluation and positional reintegration • One half of a two-person team dedicated to revamping the MSA TTPs and refining the position’s roles and responsibilities – improving efficiency and accuracy of productivity Instructor – Distributed Ground System for Special Operations Forces (DGS-SOF) Intelligence Formal Training • Conducted 440+ hours of instruction as primary instructor for the Introduction to Joint Special Operations, Tactics, Techniques and Procedures (TTPs) During Contingency Operations, Introduction to Islam, Introduction to the Multi-source Analyst (MSA) Position, mIRC, and assisted with multiple other courses to include Falconview and GoogleEarth • Instructed over 120 students; comprising members of the 11th IS, DGS-2, and associated joint service components through the exploitation of terrorist and insurgent TTPs in support of Special Operations Command and conventional military operations

summary: Current and Active TS/SCI Security Clearance w/ Counter-Intelligence Polygraph I am an active duty Air Force SIGINT Analyst with over 5 years of experience passionately pursuing professional and academic opportunities in intelligence. My academic foci have brought me subject matter expertise in all-source and OSINT analysis, interagency and multi-INT intelligence operations, intelligence analysis as both an exciting career choice and a developing field of study, and the field of public administration as it applies to America’s complex national security enterprise. My professional achievements speak to my passion and enthusiasm for mission success in intelligence analysis, collection, processing, support to strategic and tactical organizations, program management, creating and presenting intelligence briefings, national security operations, training, interagency and multinational collaboration, data validation and cross-correlation of data sets, cross-mission and multi-INT collaborative operations, and organizational leadership.

description: • Coordinated mission collaboration efforts between subordinate analysts and other intelligence organizations and activities, to include outside disciplines, tactical integration teams, Signals Development Center, and Mission Situational Awareness Cell • Established new duty positions within branch to boost target and discovery analysis efforts; wrote new training guides and standard operating procedures; managed the training of all personnel; new initiatives significantly increased collaborations and analytic output • Created and presented mission briefings to members of the US House of Representatives Intelligence Committee; selected by branch to speak on high-value target initiatives at special conference, hundreds of off-site visitors briefed • Led dozens of Personnel Recovery exercises, Operational Readiness Exercises, and quarterly training/individualized training sessions for assigned personnel; conducted official mission certifications

summary: Veteran of the U.S. Army Reserve with a vast array of law enforcement, safety, and technical experience; with impeccable commitment to community involvement, and work ethic. During my 15 month deployment as part of OIF 2008 with the military occupation specialty MP and Correction Officer In US Army I assumed responsibility as a team leader supervising 2 other MPs and was a Quad Shift Leader that maintained the daily feeding, medical care, facility maintenance and managed overall security for over 240 detainees. I documented and tracked daily headcounts for my assigned quad, reported accurately all discrepancies and compound occupancy to the Controller. I ensured all detainees were properly searched, assisted with internal roving and intelligence gathering. My efforts directly enabled coworkers to maintain 100 percent accountability of over 240 detainees. During compound searches, I showed great technical and tactical expertise in the area of searching detainees for contraband during personnel searches and also during searches of detainee living areas. My attention to detail and motivated attitude made me a valuable asset in over 50 compound searches and security sweeps, which resulted in over 2000 detainees searched and more than 25 detainee manufactured weapons removed from the detainee living areas.Specialties:Maneuver and Mobility Support Operations (such as route reconnaissance or surveillance), Area Security Operations (to include critical site security as well as response force operations), Law & Order Operations (law enforcement on US installations and host nation police force development), nternment/Resettlement Operations (includes US military prisoners as well as enemy combatants), Police Intelligence Operations

summary: Veteran of the U.S. Army Reserve with a vast array of law enforcement, safety, and technical experience; with impeccable commitment to community involvement, and work ethic. During my 15 month deployment as part of OIF 2008 with the military occupation specialty MP and Correction Officer In US Army I assumed responsibility as a team leader supervising 2 other MPs and was a Quad Shift Leader that maintained the daily feeding, medical care, facility maintenance and managed overall security for over 240 detainees. I documented and tracked daily headcounts for my assigned quad, reported accurately all discrepancies and compound occupancy to the Controller. I ensured all detainees were properly searched, assisted with internal roving and intelligence gathering. My efforts directly enabled coworkers to maintain 100 percent accountability of over 240 detainees. During compound searches, I showed great technical and tactical expertise in the area of searching detainees for contraband during personnel searches and also during searches of detainee living areas. My attention to detail and motivated attitude made me a valuable asset in over 50 compound searches and security sweeps, which resulted in over 2000 detainees searched and more than 25 detainee manufactured weapons removed from the detainee living areas.Specialties:Maneuver and Mobility Support Operations (such as route reconnaissance or surveillance), Area Security Operations (to include critical site security as well as response force operations), Law & Order Operations (law enforcement on US installations and host nation police force development), nternment/Resettlement Operations (includes US military prisoners as well as enemy combatants), Police Intelligence Operations

description: I have experience in serving during offensive operations, defensive operations and civil support operations. I have combat experience and have led a small team in the execution of Battlefield Functions. • Military police supervise or provide support to the battlefield by conducting battlefield circulation control, area security, prisoner of war operations, civilian internee operations, law and order operations on the battlefield and support to the peacetime Army community through security of critical Army resources, crime prevention programs and preservation of law and order. • The corrections specialist controls, supervises, and counsels military prisoners and manages confinement operations and correctional treatment programs. As a corrections specialist I spent 9 months in Iraq, working detainee operations with extremist groups such as Tac Fury, Sunni JAM, and Al Qaeda. The responsibilities consisted of the care, custody, and control of the detainees. Preventing self release, gathering passive intelligence, and ensuring the detainees were treated humanely and respectfully while following the guidelines directed by the SOP’s.

summary: Veteran of the U.S. Army Reserve with a vast array of law enforcement, safety, and technical experience; with impeccable commitment to community involvement, and work ethic. During my 15 month deployment as part of OIF 2008 with the military occupation specialty MP and Correction Officer In US Army I assumed responsibility as a team leader supervising 2 other MPs and was a Quad Shift Leader that maintained the daily feeding, medical care, facility maintenance and managed overall security for over 240 detainees. I documented and tracked daily headcounts for my assigned quad, reported accurately all discrepancies and compound occupancy to the Controller. I ensured all detainees were properly searched, assisted with internal roving and intelligence gathering. My efforts directly enabled coworkers to maintain 100 percent accountability of over 240 detainees. During compound searches, I showed great technical and tactical expertise in the area of searching detainees for contraband during personnel searches and also during searches of detainee living areas. My attention to detail and motivated attitude made me a valuable asset in over 50 compound searches and security sweeps, which resulted in over 2000 detainees searched and more than 25 detainee manufactured weapons removed from the detainee living areas.Specialties:Maneuver and Mobility Support Operations (such as route reconnaissance or surveillance), Area Security Operations (to include critical site security as well as response force operations), Law & Order Operations (law enforcement on US installations and host nation police force development), nternment/Resettlement Operations (includes US military prisoners as well as enemy combatants), Police Intelligence Operations

description: As a Transportation Security Officer (TSO), I perform a variety of duties related to providing security and protection of air travelers, airports and aircraft. I am required to perform passenger screening, baggage screening or both. In addition, I am expected to perform all of these duties in a courteous and professional manner. The principle duties and responsibilities include the following: • Performing security screening of persons, including tasks such as: hand-wanding (which includes the requirement to reach and wand the individual from the floor to over head), pat-down searches, and monitoring walk-through metal detector screening equipment; • Performing security screening of property, including the operation of x-ray machines to identify dangerous objects in baggage, cargo and on passengers; and preventing those objects from being transported onto aircraft; • Controlling entry and exit points; • Continuously improving security screening processes and; • Continuously improving own performance through training and development. • Continuously and effectively interact with the public, giving directions and responding to inquiries in a reasonable tone and manner; • Maintain focus and awareness and work within a stressful environment which includes noise from alarms, machinery, and people, distractions, time pressure, disruptive and angry passengers, and the requirement to identify and locate potentially life threatening devices and devices intended on creating massive destruction; and • Make effective decisions in both crisis and routine situations.
